reviews.text: Great food and service. All the food was made to perfection and you can tell they use top and fresh ingredients. But the price is on the higher end. My personal favourite was the soft shelled crab rice paper roll.

A reliable place for a good Vietnamese meal.
Summer rolls and always good, and I am a big fan of their Bun Cha.
Large on the inside and able to cater for big groups. This is a good place to have a party or gathering.

Clean and comfortable environment. The staff were also great too. Food was served relatively fast and was delicious. I would recommend this restaurants for parties bigger than 4 as the portions are as friendly for smaller parties. Highly recommend their tamarind crab.

An Nam regards itself as a high quality French-Vietnam cuisine. Although the atmosphere and ingredients are in the good quality range, the taste certainly didn’t reach the equivalent price they’re charging.

Lovely restaurant, a bit fancier than your usual Vietnamese pho place. Service is very good. 
Loved the pork neck, coconut duck curry and shrimp fried rice. Loads of flavour and the right amount of heat. 
It’s definitely a bit pricier than your average Vietnamese restaurant though. (roughly $350 per person, but this was with starters and mains - no wine or dessert). 
Would happily go again.

result.name: Gonpachi

reviews.text: Food is not fresh. The place looks dirty

Dinner on Friday night. Service is excellent, and food quality is definitely above the market competitor. 

We order around 9 dishes and enjoyed 2 hours there. No doubt it is pricy but I think it worth it. The steam egg is very recommended!

I used to despise Japanese restuarants operated by Hong Kong locals due to their lack of hygiene standard and rip-you-off mentality. But this place brings new hope to the izakaya scene in Hong Kong.

Here's a summary of what I had for dinner:
Duo tuna sashimi (meh)
Uni sushi (meh)
California roll (yum)
Veggies with crab roe dip (innovatively good)
Grilled ox tongue skewer (fantastic)
Grilled lamb chop (fantastic)
Grilled cheese (fantastic)
Hida beef Sukiyaki (Bravo)

The meal was not cheap but the fact that it was at the same price range as those dingy, wannabe izakayas located on Tang Lung Street or adjacent to SOGO whose staff received no training and washrooms are disgusting, this one is preferable.

Sitting at the tatami section, I was happy to see how the staff did not finger-grip our tea cups when refilling tea despite how low the table was. Kudos to their effort and training from managment.

However, more training is required in order to deliver a fuller experience:
1.Perfect your pronunciation of menu items. Orion the beer is pronunced as "oh-RYAN" not "orien(t)".
2.Don't drag your feet while walking in sandals(yes, servers wear sandals with socks for the convenience of serving tatami section shoeless).
3.Make sure everything is spotless clean. While I didn't dig deep to find dirt, I did question for a second if the special food containers, table, condiments, seats and the tatami floor were spotless clean.

I will be coming back.
Atmospheric setting, attentive service, excellent skewers and a very good beef noodle headline a solid pan Japanese offering.

This place is amazing👍👍 great food and excellent service. Very spacious with great lightings. Great place for celebration and for business. Amy - the supervisor was amazing. Her service was outstanding. She also recommended us some signature dishes which was really delicious. Just knew the restuarant was owned by a group named 1957 & Co. I would definitely try out their other restaurants.  Gonpachi - we would indeed return😋😋
